00:01:21.550 --> 00:01:23.320
HEWITT HEISERMAN:
The title of my talk

00:01:23.320 --> 00:01:26.480
is Ben Graham and
the Growth Investor.

00:01:26.480 --> 00:01:28.675
And if you know
anything about Ben,

00:01:28.675 --> 00:01:31.965
you know that famously
he was a value investor.

00:01:31.965 --> 00:01:34.600
He wanted to buy companies
that were cheap in relation

00:01:34.600 --> 00:01:36.270
to their corporate net worth.

00:01:36.270 --> 00:01:38.390
And this may seem
like a paradox,

00:01:38.390 --> 00:01:40.162
but I will explain
everything shortly.

00:01:43.250 --> 00:01:45.590
I want to draw your
attention to a study that

00:01:45.590 --> 00:01:50.210
was done by Jeff Smart,
a PhD, a venture capital.

00:01:50.210 --> 00:01:55.080
And these VC firms, including
some here in this area

00:01:55.080 --> 00:01:58.490
were profiled by their
personality type.

00:01:58.490 --> 00:02:01.210
And then their
performance in terms

00:02:01.210 --> 00:02:04.160
of which companies
they were investing in.

00:02:04.160 --> 00:02:06.920
Again, these are early
stage pre-revenue companies,

00:02:06.920 --> 00:02:08.904
highly speculative,
maybe just a couple

00:02:08.904 --> 00:02:12.890
of people, no
assets to speak of.

00:02:12.890 --> 00:02:15.370
The personality type
that performed the best

00:02:15.370 --> 00:02:18.150
were the airline captains.

00:02:18.150 --> 00:02:25.240
They averaged almost an 80%
IRR on their investments.

00:02:25.240 --> 00:02:28.860
The airline captain followed
a discipline repeatable

00:02:28.860 --> 00:02:31.220
and explainable
process when they

00:02:31.220 --> 00:02:35.370
were interviewing potential
candidates to finance.

00:02:35.370 --> 00:02:39.650
In other words they were
using a checklist approach.

00:02:39.650 --> 00:02:42.820
And this applies to what I'm
going to talk about today.

00:02:42.820 --> 00:02:48.000
This chart here shows that for
the last 30 years, just 25%

00:02:48.000 --> 00:02:52.900
of the stocks created all
the stock market returns.

00:02:52.900 --> 00:02:57.870
And 75% of the stocks either
broke even or they lost money.

00:02:57.870 --> 00:03:03.220
And this chart shows that one
out of five is a big winner.

00:03:03.220 --> 00:03:07.170
40% lost money and one out
of five is a big loser.

00:03:07.170 --> 00:03:11.070
So if we can tilt the odds
of success in our favor,

00:03:11.070 --> 00:03:13.680
that's a tremendous advantage.

00:03:13.680 --> 00:03:16.360
So we're going to be using
a checklist approach, which

00:03:16.360 --> 00:03:20.910
is kind of like a race, where
there's a series of hurdles.

00:03:20.910 --> 00:03:24.940
And in our approach,
not every company

00:03:24.940 --> 00:03:28.410
will reach the finish line.

00:03:28.410 --> 00:03:33.440
You probably know that
airline pilots use checklists.

00:03:33.440 --> 00:03:40.040
And even a company called
Google uses checklists.

00:03:40.040 --> 00:03:42.560
There's a great book by Atul
Gawande called, "The Checklist

00:03:42.560 --> 00:03:43.520
Manifesto."

00:03:43.520 --> 00:03:47.380
If you haven't read
it, there's a lot

00:03:47.380 --> 00:03:49.650
of good information in there.

00:03:49.650 --> 00:03:52.110
So here's our checklist
for the growth investor.

00:03:52.110 --> 00:03:54.240
We're going to go
through these five items.

00:03:54.240 --> 00:03:56.230
We're going to spend
a little more time

00:03:56.230 --> 00:04:00.730
