00:07:14.999 --> 00:07:17.290
I'm finishing a book called,
"The Checklist Manifesto,"

00:07:17.290 --> 00:07:21.060
which Miles Thompson at Columbia
University Press will publish.

00:07:21.060 --> 00:07:24.944
That should be
available in a year.

00:07:24.944 --> 00:07:26.860
Just to help you get the
lay of the land here,

00:07:26.860 --> 00:07:30.300
there are six broad reasons
why you might buy a company's

00:07:30.300 --> 00:07:35.980
stock-- yield, growth, the
company's cheap in relation

00:07:35.980 --> 00:07:40.680
to its net assets, people,
a special situation

00:07:40.680 --> 00:07:46.925
like a spin-off, and then
other includes short-selling.

00:07:46.925 --> 00:07:51.680
I'm going to address this second
column from the left, growth

00:07:51.680 --> 00:07:52.210
investing.

00:07:52.210 --> 00:07:55.010
I think this is
the most intuitive

00:07:55.010 --> 00:07:58.720
of the six approaches
or the most human.

00:07:58.720 --> 00:08:01.830
We plant a tree in our yard
and we watch the tree grow

00:08:01.830 --> 00:08:04.870
and then it has
flowers or fruit.

00:08:04.870 --> 00:08:07.140
Or if we're a
parent we have kids

00:08:07.140 --> 00:08:08.595
and we watch our kids grow up.

00:08:08.595 --> 00:08:13.490
I think we can all relate
to the growth approach.

00:08:13.490 --> 00:08:16.110
One of the great growth
stocks of the last 25 years

00:08:16.110 --> 00:08:16.880
is Microsoft.

00:08:16.880 --> 00:08:19.960
If you or your parents were
lucky or prescient enough

00:08:19.960 --> 00:08:23.930
to buy $10,000 in
1990, those shares

00:08:23.930 --> 00:08:28.000
grew to a million dollars
by the end of 1999.

00:08:28.000 --> 00:08:30.195
Now you can see in
these blue bars here--

00:08:30.195 --> 00:08:31.950
that's earnings per share.

00:08:31.950 --> 00:08:35.750
And you can see how they
keep growing over time.

00:08:35.750 --> 00:08:38.970
And that's what
Wall Street loves.

00:08:38.970 --> 00:08:42.770
There are some advantages
on a growth company--

00:08:42.770 --> 00:08:46.184
the chance to make a lot
of money, which gives you

00:08:46.184 --> 00:08:47.350
more control over your life.

00:08:47.350 --> 00:08:51.720
You may even be able to go
on and do something else,

00:08:51.720 --> 00:08:53.124
help other people.

00:08:53.124 --> 00:08:54.665
There's no exquisite
timing required.

00:08:54.665 --> 00:08:58.900
You can buy a [INAUDIBLE]
position today and then build

00:08:58.900 --> 00:09:01.380
that position as you get
to know the company better.

00:09:01.380 --> 00:09:05.660
There's no capital gains tax
so your money compounds faster.

00:09:05.660 --> 00:09:08.144
And then there is the
psychological benefit--

00:09:08.144 --> 00:09:12.140
the pride of discovery, the joy
of ownership, sort of thing.

00:09:12.140 --> 00:09:17.730
But it's important to point out
that growth investing is very

00:09:17.730 --> 00:09:25.410
difficult. Now it's not as
difficult as free climbing

00:09:25.410 --> 00:09:34.400
at Yosemite or even
getting a job here.

00:09:34.400 --> 00:09:37.960
Just to introduce the
price earnings ratio,

00:09:37.960 --> 00:09:41.580
Amazon's price is about $507.

00:09:41.580 --> 00:09:44.330
It's going to earn
about $4.46 this year.

00:09:44.330 --> 00:09:47.560
So its price to
earnings ratio is 114.

00:09:47.560 --> 00:09:51.580
If Amazon makes that same
level of earnings forever,

00:09:51.580 --> 00:09:57.590
you'll wait 114 years to get
your stock price purchase back.

00:09:57.590 --> 00:09:59.850
Alphabet's about
20 times earnings.

00:09:59.850 --> 00:10:02.160
The market's about 21 times
earnings and then Apple

00:10:02.160 --> 00:10:05.080
about 10 times earnings.

00:10:05.080 --> 00:10:07.790
I introduce the P/E
ratio because this chart

00:10:07.790 --> 00:10:10.727
shows that on the left these
are your growth companies.

00:10:10.727 --> 00:10:12.560
These are the companies
that had the highest

00:10:12.560 --> 00:10:14.400
price earnings ratio.

00:10:14.400 --> 00:10:15.960
And the companies
that we believe

00:10:15.960 --> 00:10:18.460
are going to have the most
growth in front of them,

00:10:18.460 --> 00:10:20.020
we tend to bid up their price.

00:10:20.020 --> 00:10:24.992
So they have the lowest
subsequent investment returns.

00:10:24.992 --> 00:10:26.950
And then the companies
over on the right, these

00:10:26.950 --> 00:10:30.560
are your lowest P/E stocks.

00:10:30.560 --> 00:10:34.170
And the irony is that they
had the highest returns.

00:10:34.170 --> 00:10:37.630
There are three
reasons-- three obstacles

00:10:37.630 --> 00:10:39.290
that confront the
growth investor.

00:10:39.290 --> 00:10:44.180
First of all we buy a company
that has poor earnings quality.

00:10:44.180 --> 00:10:46.980
Second, we buy a company just
as a its competitive advantage

00:10:46.980 --> 00:10:48.510
wanes.

00:10:48.510 --> 00:10:55.110
And third, we overpay for
value that never materializes.

00:10:55.110 --> 00:10:57.700
So here's our checklist that
we're going to work with today.

00:10:57.700 --> 00:11:01.080
And we're going to start with
number one, earnings quality.

00:11:01.080 --> 00:11:03.960
And to do this I want
to introduce generally

00:11:03.960 --> 00:11:05.960
accepted accounting
principals, or GAAP.

00:11:05.960 --> 00:11:09.990
GAAP is Robert's Rules
of Order for America.

00:11:09.990 --> 00:11:11.790
When you open up an
annual report or a 10-K

00:11:11.790 --> 00:11:14.020
and you look at the
financial statements,

00:11:14.020 --> 00:11:15.622
that's GAAP accounting.

00:11:15.622 --> 00:11:17.580
And we need GAAP accounting
just like motorists

00:11:17.580 --> 00:11:19.120
need traffic lights.

00:11:19.120 --> 00:11:21.538
If we didn't have
them we'd have chaos.

00:11:21.538 --> 00:11:27.400
But net income and
earnings per share, we

00:11:27.400 --> 00:11:29.750
think of them as hard
numbers or fixed numbers.

00:11:29.750 --> 00:11:33.060
But that's not the case
as I learned 30 years ago

00:11:33.060 --> 00:11:35.980
when I read this landmark
book, "Quality of Earnings,"

00:11:35.980 --> 00:11:37.760
by Thornton O'Glove.

00:11:37.760 --> 00:11:41.230
He points out in this book
that there are many accounting

00:11:41.230 --> 00:11:45.060
decisions that a CFO can make
that influence just how much

00:11:45.060 --> 00:11:49.770
or how little money
a company makes.

00:11:49.770 --> 00:11:52.920
Bill Ackman, a billionaire
hedge fund manager

00:11:52.920 --> 00:11:56.370
describes, "Quality of
Earnings" on his short list

00:11:56.370 --> 00:11:59.310
of recommended reading.

00:11:59.310 --> 00:12:02.872
Just as an aside, after
I finished my first book

00:12:02.872 --> 00:12:05.080
and I was looking for people
to write an endorsement,

00:12:05.080 --> 00:12:07.950
the first person I
called was Mr. O'Glove.

00:12:07.950 --> 00:12:09.060
I didn't know him.

00:12:09.060 --> 00:12:11.530
And we talked and
he quickly said yes.

00:12:11.530 --> 00:12:15.330
And then I found that
after that conversation,

00:12:15.330 --> 00:12:18.260
as I was asking for other
endorsements for my book,

00:12:18.260 --> 00:12:21.830
when I told them that I got the
green light from Mr. O'Glove,

00:12:21.830 --> 00:12:25.940
the endorsements came
fast and furious.

00:12:25.940 --> 00:12:27.890
He wrote just a--
just as a side note,

00:12:27.890 --> 00:12:32.800
he wrote an op-ed piece
for Barron's last fall.

00:12:32.800 --> 00:12:35.840
And he argues that
Berkshire Hathaway

00:12:35.840 --> 00:12:38.880
should-- it's time for
Berkshire to deconglomerate.

00:12:38.880 --> 00:12:44.330
It's too big and that the pieces
are worth more than the sum.

00:12:44.330 --> 00:12:46.040
So this will be an
interesting trend.

00:12:46.040 --> 00:12:49.250
It's a non-consensus view.

00:12:49.250 --> 00:12:52.700
This will be something to watch
over the next several years.

00:12:52.700 --> 00:12:55.440
Anyway, other books
that I've read which

00:12:55.440 --> 00:12:58.040
influenced by
thinking, the first,

00:12:58.040 --> 00:12:59.550
"Cash Flow and
Security Analysis"

00:12:59.550 --> 00:13:01.735
by Joshua Livnat and Ken Hackel.

00:13:01.735 --> 00:13:04.490
And they introduce what's
called a free cash flow income

00:13:04.490 --> 00:13:05.200
statement.

00:13:05.200 --> 00:13:08.590
And their argument is that the
GAAP income statement which

00:13:08.590 --> 00:13:11.670
we see here in the center,
it doesn't tell you

00:13:11.670 --> 00:13:14.410
how much cash is coming
in and out of a company.

00:13:14.410 --> 00:13:17.230
And so a better
measure is one that

00:13:17.230 --> 00:13:20.530
takes into account investment
in fixed and working capital.

00:13:20.530 --> 00:13:25.520
So let's look at that
Alphabet's results for 2015.

00:13:25.520 --> 00:13:28.120
These results were
just posted on Friday.

00:13:28.120 --> 00:13:31.205
I pulled them off
of your website.

00:13:31.205 --> 00:13:34.220
You made almost $75 billion.

00:13:34.220 --> 00:13:35.990
So I'm in the GAAP
column right now.

00:13:35.990 --> 00:13:38.650
You made $75 billion of revenue.

00:13:38.650 --> 00:13:42.120
You had $59 billion of expenses.

00:13:42.120 --> 00:13:46.080
Your net income
is $16.4 billion.

00:13:46.080 --> 00:13:51.080
And earnings per share
almost $22 a share.

00:13:51.080 --> 00:13:53.960
On a free cash flow basis, we're
going to expense investment

00:13:53.960 --> 00:13:55.067
in fixed capital.

00:13:55.067 --> 00:13:56.150
Well, what does that mean?

00:13:56.150 --> 00:14:02.830
That means if you're going
out and you're buying rockets,

00:14:02.830 --> 00:14:08.600
for example or other businesses,
or other machinery or equipment

00:14:08.600 --> 00:14:13.260
that is above your depreciation,
that is a use of cash.

00:14:13.260 --> 00:14:18.460
And depreciation is just your
old capital spending that

00:14:18.460 --> 00:14:20.610
gets written off over time.

00:14:20.610 --> 00:14:23.080
So in Alphabet's
case last year you

00:14:23.080 --> 00:14:27.600
made an investment of
$8.5 billion dollars.

00:14:27.600 --> 00:14:29.870
So that's a $8.5 billion
of cash that's coming out

00:14:29.870 --> 00:14:31.770
of your corporate
checking account

00:14:31.770 --> 00:14:35.250
that does not appear in
the GAAP income statement.

00:14:35.250 --> 00:14:36.024
Another-- yes.

00:14:36.024 --> 00:14:36.940
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE].

00:14:41.360 --> 00:14:43.110
HEWITT HEISERMAN: It's
above depreciation.

00:14:43.110 --> 00:14:44.318
That's an excellent question.

00:14:44.318 --> 00:14:45.310
Yes.

00:14:45.310 --> 00:14:47.560
What you do basically is
you take capital spending,

00:14:47.560 --> 00:14:49.090
you go to the
statement of cash flow

00:14:49.090 --> 00:14:52.390
and take capital spending
plus acquisitions

00:14:52.390 --> 00:14:54.410
minus depreciation.

00:14:54.410 --> 00:14:56.380
And the reason I
include acquisitions

00:14:56.380 --> 00:14:59.290
because many companies
buy other companies

00:14:59.290 --> 00:15:01.390
because that's a faster
way of getting up

00:15:01.390 --> 00:15:04.040
to speed than building
something de novo, where

00:15:04.040 --> 00:15:06.230
you got to hire people,
you got to get--

00:15:06.230 --> 00:15:07.850
so it's just a faster way.

00:15:07.850 --> 00:15:11.270
So $8.6 billion invested
in-- $8.5 billion

00:15:11.270 --> 00:15:13.380
invested in fixed capital.

00:15:13.380 --> 00:15:20.530
Working capital investment
is more modest, $827 million.

00:15:20.530 --> 00:15:21.740
You have some receivables.

00:15:21.740 --> 00:15:23.630
You don't have any inventory.

00:15:23.630 --> 00:15:27.333
So in the big scheme of things,
that's just a rounding error.

00:15:27.333 --> 00:15:31.690
So on a cash basis, if you
will, Alphabet last year

00:15:31.690 --> 00:15:35.455
made $5.96 billion.

00:15:35.455 --> 00:15:38.150
And one thing I like to
look at is I like to see,

00:15:38.150 --> 00:15:42.820
what's the percentage
of free cash flow

00:15:42.820 --> 00:15:45.050
earnings to GAAP earnings.

00:15:45.050 --> 00:15:49.730
And here we see
that ratio is 37%.

00:15:49.730 --> 00:15:52.246
So that idea is from
this book, "Cash Flow

00:15:52.246 --> 00:15:53.400
and Security Analysis."

00:15:53.400 --> 00:15:56.590
I then read another book
called, "The Quest for Value,"

00:15:56.590 --> 00:15:58.600
after reading about Coca-Cole.

00:15:58.600 --> 00:16:03.630
There was a cover story in
Fortune magazine, 1995, 1996,

00:16:03.630 --> 00:16:08.920
and Roberto Goizueta who was
the CEO was lauding this EVA

00:16:08.920 --> 00:16:12.110
approach to capital allocation.

00:16:12.110 --> 00:16:18.474
And Coke at that time had
a 10-year track record

00:16:18.474 --> 00:16:23.780
of creating some serious
amounts of stockholder wealth.

00:16:23.780 --> 00:16:28.300
This EVA income statement is
unique for its own two reasons.

00:16:28.300 --> 00:16:31.960
Now you'll notice that it
does not expense investment

00:16:31.960 --> 00:16:35.330
in working capital, at
least not immediately.

00:16:35.330 --> 00:16:39.700
What it does expense directly
is intangibles like R&amp;D, money

00:16:39.700 --> 00:16:42.516
that you spend on patents.

00:16:42.516 --> 00:16:44.570
These would be relevant
for your business.

00:16:44.570 --> 00:16:48.170
Other businesses,
it might be the cost

00:16:48.170 --> 00:16:51.160
of buying subscription
lists or marketing efforts,

00:16:51.160 --> 00:16:53.120
pre-store opening costs.

00:16:53.120 --> 00:16:56.460
So I want you to compare the
difference between the GAAP

00:16:56.460 --> 00:16:59.720
expense for intangibles
and the EVA approach.

00:16:59.720 --> 00:17:01.750
There's about a $4
billion difference.

00:17:01.750 --> 00:17:04.839
The EVA approach
actually credits

00:17:04.839 --> 00:17:07.990
you back about $4 billion
worth of expenses.

00:17:07.990 --> 00:17:11.740
Because the mindset
here is, we're

00:17:11.740 --> 00:17:14.050
going to spread
those intangibles

00:17:14.050 --> 00:17:15.710
over their expected useful life.

00:17:15.710 --> 00:17:19.560
So if you're investing in
your people, your processes,

00:17:19.560 --> 00:17:22.099
or your intellectual
property today,

00:17:22.099 --> 00:17:27.940
we don't expect you to derive
value from those outlays today.

00:17:27.940 --> 00:17:32.607
We think they'll occur in year
two, three, four, five, six.

00:17:32.607 --> 00:17:34.440
So we're going to try
to match current sales

00:17:34.440 --> 00:17:38.880
with current expenses and future
sales with future expenses.

00:17:38.880 --> 00:17:41.520
The other income statement
here that's noteworthy

00:17:41.520 --> 00:17:43.550
is the interest expense
or cost of capital

00:17:43.550 --> 00:17:46.880
which is about $5.7 billion.

00:17:46.880 --> 00:17:53.870
In the EVA approach, not only
is debt treated as an expense

00:17:53.870 --> 00:17:59.710
but so is stockholder's equity,
which you have a lot of.

00:17:59.710 --> 00:18:05.140
So in the EVA approach, if you
buy Alphabet stock or you buy

00:18:05.140 --> 00:18:08.390
Coca-Cola stock--
Procter &amp; Gamble stock,

00:18:08.390 --> 00:18:10.080
you have an expected
return mindset.

00:18:10.080 --> 00:18:13.570
You expect to get some
return on your stock.

00:18:13.570 --> 00:18:16.030
And so what the EVA
approach tries to do

00:18:16.030 --> 00:18:18.200
is to capture that cost.

00:18:18.200 --> 00:18:20.050
Now if accounting's
not your thing,

00:18:20.050 --> 00:18:24.520
the good news is, that's the
end of the accounting for today.

00:18:24.520 --> 00:18:25.570
So I was in a quandary.

00:18:25.570 --> 00:18:27.880
When do I use the free
cash flow income statement

00:18:27.880 --> 00:18:30.334
and when do I use the
EVA income statement?

00:18:30.334 --> 00:18:32.900
And I built both of
these alternate income

00:18:32.900 --> 00:18:36.385
statements in Excel on my
computer, and I had them

00:18:36.385 --> 00:18:38.010
and I just didn't
know which way to go.

00:18:38.010 --> 00:18:42.810
And then I read a passage from
one of Ben Graham's books.

00:18:42.810 --> 00:18:48.120
Now Ben is the
first great investor

00:18:48.120 --> 00:18:49.310
teacher of the modern age.

00:18:49.310 --> 00:18:52.870
He came to the United States
with his family, graduated

00:18:52.870 --> 00:18:55.390
from Columbia with
three offers to teach

00:18:55.390 --> 00:18:57.070
at three different departments.

00:18:57.070 --> 00:18:58.345
His father just passed away.

00:18:58.345 --> 00:19:01.829
He needed to make some money for
his mother and two younger sons

00:19:01.829 --> 00:19:03.120
so he got a job on Wall Street.

00:19:03.120 --> 00:19:05.346
And he started making a
lot of money pretty quick.

00:19:05.346 --> 00:19:07.720
And then the depression came
along and he was speculating

00:19:07.720 --> 00:19:09.480
and Ben got wiped out.

00:19:09.480 --> 00:19:13.810
So he re-jigged his
investment methodology

00:19:13.810 --> 00:19:16.530
and he developed this margin
of safety principle, which

00:19:16.530 --> 00:19:18.180
you're probably familiar with.

00:19:18.180 --> 00:19:20.720
And we all use margin
of safety in our lives.

00:19:20.720 --> 00:19:22.800
If you have to be at work
at-- what time do you

00:19:22.800 --> 00:19:24.074
have to be at work here?

00:19:24.074 --> 00:19:25.280
[LAUGHTER]

00:19:25.280 --> 00:19:26.080
AUDIENCE: Whenever.

00:19:26.080 --> 00:19:26.520
HEWITT HEISERMAN: Whenever.

00:19:26.520 --> 00:19:29.020
All right, if you have
to be here at whenever,

00:19:29.020 --> 00:19:30.670
and you know it
takes a half hour,

00:19:30.670 --> 00:19:35.380
you leave 45 minutes before,
just in case something happens.

00:19:35.380 --> 00:19:40.296
So that was his framework for
approaching stock selection.

00:19:43.600 --> 00:19:46.530
Warren Buffett explains
margin of safety this way.

00:19:46.530 --> 00:19:51.430
He says, "you build a bridge
that can carry a 30,000 pound

00:19:51.430 --> 00:19:56.760
truck but then you have a
weight limit of 10,000 pounds."

00:19:56.760 --> 00:20:00.010
Now, Alphabet has
a margin of safety.

00:20:00.010 --> 00:20:02.500
It's a redundancy.

00:20:02.500 --> 00:20:08.070
It is your data centers that
you have around the world.

00:20:08.070 --> 00:20:09.330
And I assume you have them.

00:20:09.330 --> 00:20:12.351
You had them as of last week.

00:20:12.351 --> 00:20:12.850
Right?

00:20:12.850 --> 00:20:13.850
So it's the same idea.

00:20:13.850 --> 00:20:14.850
It's a margin of safety.

00:20:14.850 --> 00:20:16.970
If one data center
goes down, you've

00:20:16.970 --> 00:20:21.057
got others that you can use.

00:20:21.057 --> 00:20:23.140
Anyway, Ben writes in the,
"Intelligent Investor,"

00:20:23.140 --> 00:20:26.430
he says there are two types--
the defensive investor who

00:20:26.430 --> 00:20:29.030
wants to avoid committing
[INAUDIBLE] mistakes,

00:20:29.030 --> 00:20:30.760
and the enterprising
investor who

00:20:30.760 --> 00:20:33.846
wants to own companies that
are more promising than most.

00:20:33.846 --> 00:20:34.970
So I'm thinking about this.

00:20:34.970 --> 00:20:38.050
I'm thinking, huh,
the defensive investor

00:20:38.050 --> 00:20:40.950
is kind of like a
commercial banker.

00:20:40.950 --> 00:20:44.880
If it's raining, they want the
umbrella that they lent you.

00:20:44.880 --> 00:20:46.250
They want it back.

00:20:46.250 --> 00:20:48.430
And they think about
corporate profitability kind

00:20:48.430 --> 00:20:49.590
of like a lemonade stand.

00:20:49.590 --> 00:20:51.710
Because the way that
they're going to make

00:20:51.710 --> 00:20:54.270
money is if you can
repay that loan.

00:20:54.270 --> 00:20:58.310
And so they're going to focus
on how much cash you generate.

00:20:58.310 --> 00:21:01.930
Their not going to get
rich owning your business.

00:21:01.930 --> 00:21:06.140
So their mindset is very
pessimistic, hard money.

00:21:06.140 --> 00:21:09.130
And that's the way the free cash
flow income statement works.

00:21:09.130 --> 00:21:11.620
And then the other
personality type,

00:21:11.620 --> 00:21:14.470
I think of it as like the
way a venture capitalist

00:21:14.470 --> 00:21:15.530
looks at a business.

00:21:15.530 --> 00:21:23.370
Here at Alphabet, you have
two funding entities, right?

00:21:23.370 --> 00:21:25.360
They're both early stage.

00:21:25.360 --> 00:21:28.620
This is according to what
I read in the papers.

00:21:28.620 --> 00:21:32.930
When they sit down and they
look at business opportunities,

00:21:32.930 --> 00:21:34.730
they're creating a pro forma.

00:21:34.730 --> 00:21:39.330
So they're modeling out
revenue going out several years

00:21:39.330 --> 00:21:41.380
and then they're
modeling out expenses.

00:21:41.380 --> 00:21:44.120
They're going to
depreciate or spread

00:21:44.120 --> 00:21:49.280
over time intangibles
and capital spending.

00:21:49.280 --> 00:21:51.610
But also they want
to make a return.

00:21:51.610 --> 00:21:53.640
Because your stockholders
want to make a return.

00:21:53.640 --> 00:21:56.630
So they're going to have a
line in there for the financing

00:21:56.630 --> 00:21:59.420
that they're providing
to this entity.

00:21:59.420 --> 00:22:01.827
So I want to make a proposal
that the GAAP income

00:22:01.827 --> 00:22:03.410
statement is too,
"venture capitalist"

00:22:03.410 --> 00:22:07.890
for the defensive
investor and is too,

00:22:07.890 --> 00:22:12.290
"commercial banker" for
the enterprising investor.

00:22:12.290 --> 00:22:14.049
And now we're going
to return to Alphabet

00:22:14.049 --> 00:22:15.590
and we're going to
look at five years

00:22:15.590 --> 00:22:17.500
worth of your performance.

00:22:17.500 --> 00:22:19.920
Now the blue bar, that's
your GAAP net income.

00:22:19.920 --> 00:22:22.220
And that's in the
middle because it's

00:22:22.220 --> 00:22:26.280
kind of in between these two
opposing viewpoints about what

00:22:26.280 --> 00:22:28.970
is corporate profitability.

00:22:28.970 --> 00:22:34.599
We see a progression of
increased positive progression

00:22:34.599 --> 00:22:35.640
over the last five years.

00:22:35.640 --> 00:22:37.080
So that's impressive.

00:22:37.080 --> 00:22:40.570
We have our defensive
profits on the left.

00:22:40.570 --> 00:22:46.020
And you see that
beginning in 2013,

00:22:46.020 --> 00:22:51.160
the gap between GAAP
net income has widened.

00:22:51.160 --> 00:22:54.600
And that's because you're making
tremendous investments in fixed

00:22:54.600 --> 00:22:55.270
capital.

00:22:55.270 --> 00:22:57.960
Now if you had a
lot of debt, if you

00:22:57.960 --> 00:23:03.400
had a history of write-offs,
if your ownership culture--

00:23:03.400 --> 00:23:05.850
if I wasn't comfortable
with your ownership culture,

00:23:05.850 --> 00:23:07.930
if I looked at
this dichotomy, it

00:23:07.930 --> 00:23:11.140
would make me somewhat troubled.

00:23:11.140 --> 00:23:14.130
In Alphabet's case,
there's nothing

00:23:14.130 --> 00:23:18.490
to suggest that these
investments in the future

00:23:18.490 --> 00:23:21.010
are anything to worry about.

00:23:21.010 --> 00:23:23.380
With the enterprise
income statement,

00:23:23.380 --> 00:23:26.590
we can see that
there's a tighter

00:23:26.590 --> 00:23:30.470
correlation between GAAP
profits and enterprise profits.

00:23:30.470 --> 00:23:32.830
So this gives me
comfort that you're

00:23:32.830 --> 00:23:38.910
making pretty high
returns on your earnings.

00:23:38.910 --> 00:23:40.530
Most of what I'm
talking about today,

00:23:40.530 --> 00:23:42.905
these are ideas that
I've collated and thought

00:23:42.905 --> 00:23:44.030
about from other investors.

00:23:44.030 --> 00:23:48.260
I guess my one little
contribution to this field,

00:23:48.260 --> 00:23:52.399
such as it is, is what I call
the earnings power chart.

00:23:52.399 --> 00:23:53.940
And so in this
approach, we are going

00:23:53.940 --> 00:23:55.700
to reject the GAAP
income statement,

00:23:55.700 --> 00:23:58.197
because it's like
being half pregnant.

00:23:58.197 --> 00:24:00.530
We're going to focus on the
relationship between defense

00:24:00.530 --> 00:24:02.570
and enterprise in profits.

00:24:02.570 --> 00:24:07.030
And as you would think, the
best-- there are four boxes.

00:24:07.030 --> 00:24:09.520
And the best box to be is
in the upper right box.

00:24:09.520 --> 00:24:13.320
That means you have defensive
profits and enterprise profits.

00:24:13.320 --> 00:24:18.065
And that's where Alphabet
has resided for the last five

00:24:18.065 --> 00:24:18.565
years.

00:24:21.370 --> 00:24:23.200
We're now going to
step back 15 years

00:24:23.200 --> 00:24:26.190
to a company called Enron.

00:24:26.190 --> 00:24:33.230
Enron, in the late 1990s was one
of the best performing stocks.

00:24:33.230 --> 00:24:36.730
It was a stock to last a decade.

00:24:36.730 --> 00:24:41.750
This is of the 2000s, according
to a business publication

00:24:41.750 --> 00:24:43.810
that's prominent.

00:24:43.810 --> 00:24:47.510
Its CFO Andy Fastow
was named best

00:24:47.510 --> 00:24:51.280
CFO, chief financial officer.

00:24:51.280 --> 00:24:52.980
And a lot of people
were buying Enron

00:24:52.980 --> 00:24:55.770
because they thought it
was a growth company.

00:24:55.770 --> 00:24:59.050
Their thesis was based
on the income statement.

00:24:59.050 --> 00:25:02.170
But when we look at
their earnings quality

00:25:02.170 --> 00:25:04.030
through these two
alternate metrics,

00:25:04.030 --> 00:25:07.620
we see that they were in the
lower left box every year.

00:25:07.620 --> 00:25:11.680
So if you were thinking
of buying Enron

00:25:11.680 --> 00:25:14.540
and you ran those numbers
through this model,

00:25:14.540 --> 00:25:17.329
you'd have to
reject that thesis.

00:25:17.329 --> 00:25:19.620
There might have been other
reasons to buy the company,

00:25:19.620 --> 00:25:22.640
but it wasn't because of their
quality of their earnings

00:25:22.640 --> 00:25:24.730
growth.

00:25:24.730 --> 00:25:28.000
After I finished
looking at Enron,

00:25:28.000 --> 00:25:32.450
I wondered, did either of these
two alternate income statements

00:25:32.450 --> 00:25:35.030
or maybe the earning pie
chart tell you in advance

00:25:35.030 --> 00:25:37.520
that something was wrong with
all these other companies?

00:25:37.520 --> 00:25:39.540
All these other
companies here, they all

00:25:39.540 --> 00:25:43.258
ran into financial difficulty
and cost stockholders lots

00:25:43.258 --> 00:25:44.756
of money.

00:25:44.756 --> 00:25:46.380
And so I wanted to
be like a-- I wanted

00:25:46.380 --> 00:25:48.730
to see if there is
something you could

00:25:48.730 --> 00:25:53.280
have known before the carnage.

00:25:53.280 --> 00:25:57.140
And what I found is that often
the defensive income statement

00:25:57.140 --> 00:26:00.520
told you that the company
had poor earnings quality

00:26:00.520 --> 00:26:02.690
and you should go on high alert.

00:26:02.690 --> 00:26:05.710
And often it was the
enterprising income statement.

00:26:05.710 --> 00:26:09.360
And then sometimes it was both
alternate income statements

00:26:09.360 --> 00:26:12.072
as we see with Enron.

00:26:12.072 --> 00:26:12.988
