the accrual ratio.

00:28:16.250 --> 00:28:18.680
And the accrual ratio may have
picked up similar problems.

00:28:18.680 --> 00:28:22.070
But the reason why I like seeing
the three income statements

00:28:22.070 --> 00:28:25.000
side by side, because you can
just go through each expense,

00:28:25.000 --> 00:28:29.886
and you look for something
that's out of the ordinary.

00:28:29.886 --> 00:28:31.510
And then you can take
that information,

00:28:31.510 --> 00:28:33.135
you can take like
their investment rate

00:28:33.135 --> 00:28:35.050
in fixed capital and
you can compare it

00:28:35.050 --> 00:28:36.920
to the industry average.

00:28:36.920 --> 00:28:38.630
So it's really like
a jumping off point

00:28:38.630 --> 00:28:43.240
for to do further research if
you see something that's wrong.

00:28:43.240 --> 00:28:44.320
OK.

00:28:44.320 --> 00:28:46.220
Enough of failure.

00:28:46.220 --> 00:28:47.870
Let's look at success.

00:28:47.870 --> 00:28:50.590
Here is Microsoft
during the 1990s.

00:28:50.590 --> 00:28:54.600
Remember, this company
turned a hypothetical $10,000

00:28:54.600 --> 00:28:56.120
into a million dollars.

00:28:56.120 --> 00:28:59.830
This is what we call--
to use Peter Lynch's

00:28:59.830 --> 00:29:02.790
description, a 100 bagger.

00:29:02.790 --> 00:29:05.510
What we see here--
I see three things.

00:29:05.510 --> 00:29:09.240
Number one, the company
is in the upper right box,

00:29:09.240 --> 00:29:11.630
so it has high quality earnings.

00:29:11.630 --> 00:29:14.920
Number two, it's moving
every year in an upper right

00:29:14.920 --> 00:29:16.520
direction.

00:29:16.520 --> 00:29:18.840
So I call this an
earnings power staircase.

00:29:18.840 --> 00:29:21.640
This is a sign of
profitable growth.

00:29:21.640 --> 00:29:24.930
Not only is the company getting
bigger but it's getting better.

00:29:24.930 --> 00:29:26.670
And then third, a
couple of these years,

00:29:26.670 --> 00:29:29.680
look at the rate of change
from one year-- look at '97

00:29:29.680 --> 00:29:31.660
to '98 and then '98 to '99.

00:29:31.660 --> 00:29:33.810
It's just explosive growth.

00:29:33.810 --> 00:29:36.004
And this is what
Wall Street loves.

00:29:38.770 --> 00:29:41.997
There is a great book Chris
Mayer called, "100 Baggers."

00:29:41.997 --> 00:29:44.330
If you want to learn more
about these kinds of companies

00:29:44.330 --> 00:29:45.550
I highly recommend this book.

00:29:45.550 --> 00:29:48.630
It came out last fall.

00:29:48.630 --> 00:29:53.890
We're now going to look at other
companies that had earnings

00:29:53.890 --> 00:29:55.500
power staircase-like patterns.

00:29:55.500 --> 00:29:57.890
And we're just going to go
through this kind of fast.

00:29:57.890 --> 00:30:00.010
But I just want
you to appreciate

00:30:00.010 --> 00:30:04.430
that positive trajectory
in high quality earnings.

00:30:04.430 --> 00:30:07.910
[INAUDIBLE] turned
$10,000 into $44,000.

00:30:07.910 --> 00:30:11.410
First Cash Financial,
$10,000 into $86,000.

00:30:11.410 --> 00:30:14.170
Apollo Group, $10
grand into $78,000.

00:30:14.170 --> 00:30:17.640
Dell Computer, $10
grand into $1.3 million.

00:30:17.640 --> 00:30:20.982
Cisco Systems, $10
grand into $631,000.

00:30:20.982 --> 00:30:24.490
Paychex, $10,000 into $257,000.

00:30:24.490 --> 00:30:27.540
Quality systems,
$10,000 into of $70,000.

00:30:27.540 --> 00:30:31.650
Hansen Natural, $10,000
into $2.6 million.

00:30:31.650 --> 00:30:34.880
Chico's FAS $10,000
into $73,000.

00:30:34.880 --> 00:30:38.620
Monster Beverage,
$10,000 into $61,000.

00:30:38.620 --> 00:30:40.520
Monster's interesting
because this

00:30:40.520 --> 00:30:43.770
is the best performing
stock of the last 20 years.

00:30:43.770 --> 00:30:49.050
A hypothetical $10000
investment grew to $10 million.

00:30:49.050 --> 00:30:52.530
We're going to turn this
presentation into a book,

00:30:52.530 --> 00:30:57.420
and I'll have much more to
say about Monster in the book.

00:30:57.420 --> 00:31:01.030
So if your thesis is growth,
if you're a growth investor,

00:31:01.030 --> 00:31:03.970
I want you to focus on companies
that are in the upper right box

00:31:03.970 --> 00:31:07.060
and that are moving in an upward
right direction every year,

00:31:07.060 --> 00:31:10.040
forging what I call an
earnings power staircase.

00:31:10.040 --> 00:31:13.380
These are the companies
that have profitable growth.

00:31:13.380 --> 00:31:20.300
And the next step is,
in our checklist here

00:31:20.300 --> 00:31:21.750
is competitive advantage.

00:31:21.750 --> 00:31:23.980
If a company is
forging a staircase,

00:31:23.980 --> 00:31:26.690
it probably has a
competitive advantage.

00:31:26.690 --> 00:31:28.440
There are five types.

00:31:28.440 --> 00:31:30.660
If you saw Pat
Dorsey's presentation

00:31:30.660 --> 00:31:33.580
here about a year
ago-- Pat is the expert

00:31:33.580 --> 00:31:35.490
on competitive advantage.

00:31:35.490 --> 00:31:38.845
When he was with Morning
Star he and his staff teased

00:31:38.845 --> 00:31:40.220
out four competitive
advantages--

00:31:40.220 --> 00:31:43.150
low cost, provider
high switching costs,

00:31:43.150 --> 00:31:47.770
intangibles like brands and
patents and that sort of thing,

00:31:47.770 --> 00:31:52.500
and then network effect,
the telephone, Facebook,

00:31:52.500 --> 00:31:53.760
that sort of thing.

00:31:53.760 --> 00:31:57.170
And then I add to
that list, ecosystems.

00:31:57.170 --> 00:32:01.390
So if you make a
gadget, and the gadget

00:32:01.390 --> 00:32:03.610
can talk to another
gadget that's

00:32:03.610 --> 00:32:05.200
made by the same
company, then you

00:32:05.200 --> 00:32:09.770
can transfer all that data go
as new versions of the gadget

00:32:09.770 --> 00:32:10.475
come out.

00:32:10.475 --> 00:32:12.110
That to me is an ecosystem.

00:32:12.110 --> 00:32:13.960
With a network effect,
the more people

00:32:13.960 --> 00:32:15.730
you have, the more
valuable the network.

00:32:15.730 --> 00:32:17.800
But in theory, in an
ecosystem, you really

00:32:17.800 --> 00:32:20.150
only need one customer.

00:32:20.150 --> 00:32:23.120
Warren Buffet describes
a competitive advantage

00:32:23.120 --> 00:32:24.680
as a moat.

00:32:24.680 --> 00:32:30.510
And I bet that Larry
and Sergey and Eric

00:32:30.510 --> 00:32:34.500
probably spend most of their
time thinking about this issue.

00:32:34.500 --> 00:32:37.310
The castle is
Alphabet, and the moat

00:32:37.310 --> 00:32:42.200
is whatever you guys,
men and women can come up

00:32:42.200 --> 00:32:46.280
with that prevents the
competition from taking

00:32:46.280 --> 00:32:49.270
your business.

00:32:49.270 --> 00:32:51.062
Warren Buffett
says that if there

00:32:51.062 --> 00:32:53.020
are alligators in the
moat, that's even better.

00:32:55.540 --> 00:32:59.680
We're not going to talk
about competitive advantage

00:32:59.680 --> 00:33:03.320
except to say that if you
determine that a company has

00:33:03.320 --> 00:33:05.440
a competitive advantage,
and it probably

00:33:05.440 --> 00:33:07.870
does if it's
forging a staircase,

00:33:07.870 --> 00:33:12.070
then you want to think
about the drivers that

00:33:12.070 --> 00:33:15.730
affect intrinsic value.

00:33:15.730 --> 00:33:18.670
Companies that have a
competitive advantage,

00:33:18.670 --> 00:33:20.880
they're more valuable
than companies that don't

00:33:20.880 --> 00:33:22.110
have a competitive advantage.

00:33:22.110 --> 00:33:25.480
If you sell a
commodity, you really

00:33:25.480 --> 00:33:27.020
don't have any pricing power.

00:33:27.020 --> 00:33:29.310
People will go buy your
product from someone else

00:33:29.310 --> 00:33:32.890
if they can get a better deal.

00:33:32.890 --> 00:33:37.940
Intrinsic value
is our third step.

00:33:37.940 --> 00:33:42.480
That's what the fair
worth of the business is.

00:33:42.480 --> 00:33:45.850
Morningstar-- they do
a lot of great work

00:33:45.850 --> 00:33:49.865
with estimating companies
intrinsic value.

00:33:49.865 --> 00:33:55.870
They project that the business--
Alphabet's worth $755 a share.

00:33:55.870 --> 00:33:59.230
The stock price as of
last week was $682.

00:33:59.230 --> 00:34:03.070
So the price to
intrinsic value is 90%.

00:34:03.070 --> 00:34:06.700
If you buy Alphabet stock
today, you're paying $0.90 cents

00:34:06.700 --> 00:34:08.790
for a dollar's worth of value.

00:34:08.790 --> 00:34:12.110
If you knew that,
for whatever reason,

00:34:12.110 --> 00:34:16.710
the price intrinsic value
was going to go down to 75%,

00:34:16.710 --> 00:34:18.460
then you would wait
because then you'd

00:34:18.460 --> 00:34:20.441
get even more value
for your money.

00:34:23.360 --> 00:34:27.920
Professor [INAUDIBLE]
spoke to your group.

00:34:27.920 --> 00:34:30.530
And if you want to learn
more about valuation,

00:34:30.530 --> 00:34:35.300
check out his presentation
which is excellent.

00:34:35.300 --> 00:34:39.909
It's getting harder to estimate
a company's intrinsic value

00:34:39.909 --> 00:34:42.035
because if you have
to make assumptions

00:34:42.035 --> 00:34:43.909
about how long the
business is going to last.

00:34:43.909 --> 00:34:48.550
And as this research shows,
in five years from today,

00:34:48.550 --> 00:34:51.735
32% of US public companies
will be out of business.

00:34:51.735 --> 00:34:53.610
They'll be either acquired
by other companies

00:34:53.610 --> 00:34:55.190
or they'll just go bankrupt.

00:34:55.190 --> 00:34:57.560
Versus 50 years
ago, it was only 5%.

00:34:57.560 --> 00:35:01.390
So the rate of change
is accelerating,

00:35:01.390 --> 00:35:03.810
and for better or
for worse, Alphabet

00:35:03.810 --> 00:35:05.145
is one of the prime disruptors.

00:35:09.220 --> 00:35:12.960
One item I want to point out
that is something to watch

00:35:12.960 --> 00:35:21.750
is that your incremental
capital is trending down.

00:35:21.750 --> 00:35:25.690
You're making bets that are
outside your core business.

00:35:25.690 --> 00:35:27.600
Hopefully those bets
will pay off and then

00:35:27.600 --> 00:35:28.890
that trend will reverse.

00:35:28.890 --> 00:35:30.780
This will be something to watch.

00:35:30.780 --> 00:35:32.870
To learn more about
intrinsic value

00:35:32.870 --> 00:35:35.490
there's a great resource,
Valuentum Securities

00:35:35.490 --> 00:35:38.090
which I subscribe to
and I highly recommend.

00:35:38.090 --> 00:35:40.490
And I mentioned earlier,
Old School Value

00:35:40.490 --> 00:35:41.790
which I also subscribe to.

00:35:41.790 --> 00:35:47.645
They give you 10 years worth
of financial statements.

00:35:47.645 --> 00:35:50.020
Just type in the symbol and
the information's right there

00:35:50.020 --> 00:35:52.121
and they have a lot of
pre-programmed valuation

00:35:52.121 --> 00:35:52.620
models.

00:35:52.620 --> 00:35:54.200
So you don't have to build
the thing from scratch

00:35:54.200 --> 00:35:56.180
and spend a couple
of weeks doing that.

00:35:56.180 --> 00:35:59.557
All the information's
right at your fingertips.

00:35:59.557 --> 00:36:01.140
Now I mentioned that
Ben Graham-- yes.

00:36:01.140 --> 00:36:03.515
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE]?

00:36:03.515 --> 00:36:04.940
MALE SPEAKER: Yeah, he will be.

00:36:04.940 --> 00:36:05.900
HEWITT HEISERMAN: Yep.

00:36:05.900 --> 00:36:12.150
I've mentioned that Ben was
affected by the depression.

00:36:12.150 --> 00:36:15.800
And so he took a hard money
approach to buying stocks.

00:36:15.800 --> 00:36:18.770
So his method was
what he called--

00:36:18.770 --> 00:36:22.390
this is after he figured
out a new approach.

00:36:22.390 --> 00:36:24.610
He would buy companies
that were selling at 2/3

00:36:24.610 --> 00:36:27.750
of their net working capital.

00:36:27.750 --> 00:36:36.306
So taking your balance sheet
from December 31, 2015.

00:36:36.306 --> 00:36:39.670
He gave 100% for your cash.

00:36:39.670 --> 00:36:41.580
He'd give you a 75%
for your receivables.

00:36:41.580 --> 00:36:43.750
You don't have any inventory.

00:36:43.750 --> 00:36:45.877
And then he'd subtract
all your liabilities.

00:36:45.877 --> 00:36:47.710
And then he'd take your
net working capital,

00:36:47.710 --> 00:36:52.000
he'd multiply that
by 66% of that.

00:36:52.000 --> 00:36:54.060
And then that would
leave you $36 billion.

00:36:54.060 --> 00:36:56.425
He would pay $36 billion
for the business.

00:36:56.425 --> 00:37:01.580
You've got 745 million shares
outstanding, so he'd paid $45.

00:37:01.580 --> 00:37:05.040
Is that right? $48 for Google.

00:37:05.040 --> 00:37:05.540
All right.

00:37:05.540 --> 00:37:08.300
That's what he would buy it for.

00:37:08.300 --> 00:37:08.930
All right.

00:37:08.930 --> 00:37:13.040
Now we're at step
four, position sizing.

00:37:13.040 --> 00:37:15.200
Position sizing is
simply, what percentage

00:37:15.200 --> 00:37:16.710
of your portfolio
or your capital

00:37:16.710 --> 00:37:19.300
are you going to put
into any single position?

00:37:19.300 --> 00:37:22.686
Now it stands to reason
that if you have an edge,

00:37:22.686 --> 00:37:23.810
then you should exploit it.

00:37:23.810 --> 00:37:28.490
And this is what Warren Buffett
did after the famous salad oil

00:37:28.490 --> 00:37:30.790
scandal in 1963.

00:37:30.790 --> 00:37:35.040
It knocked shares of
American Express down.

00:37:35.040 --> 00:37:39.090
Mr. Buffet determined that
American Express' franchise was

00:37:39.090 --> 00:37:46.010
intact, and he put 40%
of the partnerships funds

00:37:46.010 --> 00:37:49.056
into American Express and
it then went up five-fold

00:37:49.056 --> 00:37:51.640
in five years.

00:37:51.640 --> 00:37:53.860
You really have to be
honest with yourself

00:37:53.860 --> 00:37:56.010
though in terms of whether
or not you have an edge.

00:37:56.010 --> 00:38:02.740
There are four types--
information, analytic,

00:38:02.740 --> 00:38:07.430
behavioral, and structural.

00:38:07.430 --> 00:38:10.030
You also want to
ask yourself, what's

00:38:10.030 --> 00:38:14.130
the consequence if I
am wrong, and can I

00:38:14.130 --> 00:38:16.910
afford that consequence?

00:38:16.910 --> 00:38:19.182
My advice is, if you
don't have an edge,

00:38:19.182 --> 00:38:21.390
you start small, especially
with these growth

00:38:21.390 --> 00:38:26.300
companies because we see how
core the subsequent investment

00:38:26.300 --> 00:38:27.440
returns are.

00:38:27.440 --> 00:38:29.097
And then build your
position over time

00:38:29.097 --> 00:38:30.680
as you get to know
the company better.

00:38:30.680 --> 00:38:33.335
You may get a better entry
point in terms of price

00:38:33.335 --> 00:38:36.000
to intrinsic value.

00:38:36.000 --> 00:38:39.030
And absolutely positively
have a sell strategy,

00:38:39.030 --> 00:38:42.440
which is something we'll
cover here in a short moment.

00:38:42.440 --> 00:38:45.780
For men especially,
you've got to guard

00:38:45.780 --> 00:38:47.410
against overconfidence.

00:38:47.410 --> 00:38:50.000
And there are people that have
gotten PhD's on this topic.

00:38:50.000 --> 00:38:52.020
I'm not going to talk
about it at length.

00:38:52.020 --> 00:38:53.450
You can look into
it if you want.

00:38:53.450 --> 00:38:56.860
But Curt Schilling--
we live in Boston.

00:38:56.860 --> 00:39:00.310
Curt Schilling of the
famous bloody sock,

00:39:00.310 --> 00:39:04.430
retired, he was into games and
started a business, 38 Studios.

00:39:04.430 --> 00:39:07.920
He put his entire $50 million
net worth into the business,

00:39:07.920 --> 00:39:10.850
and then business went bankrupt.

00:39:10.850 --> 00:39:14.300
Other examples of overconfidence
include the Hunt brothers

00:39:14.300 --> 00:39:18.500
with silver in the 1970s
and then long-term capital

00:39:18.500 --> 00:39:20.600
management.

00:39:20.600 --> 00:39:23.150
I had my own
overconfidence story.

00:39:23.150 --> 00:39:28.150
I invested in China
Media Express in 2011.

00:39:28.150 --> 00:39:33.460
It seemingly passed the
three checklist items

00:39:33.460 --> 00:39:35.920
that we've just
discussed-- high quality

00:39:35.920 --> 00:39:38.970
earnings, competitive
advantage, and it was cheap.

00:39:38.970 --> 00:39:41.860
It was selling at eight times
earnings, had $200 million

00:39:41.860 --> 00:39:47.856
of cash, no debt, audited
financials by Deloitte.

00:39:47.856 --> 00:39:50.630
Hank Greenberg,
who had built AIG

00:39:50.630 --> 00:39:52.780
into one the preeminent
insurance companies,

00:39:52.780 --> 00:39:56.630
he had put $80 million
into China Media Express.

00:39:56.630 --> 00:39:59.500
And one of his colleagues
was on the board.

00:39:59.500 --> 00:40:02.730
But, alas, China Media
Express was a fraud.

00:40:02.730 --> 00:40:04.226
There was no $200 million.

00:40:07.730 --> 00:40:11.120
So after the grieving
process was over,

00:40:11.120 --> 00:40:15.150
I determined that I was going
to turn lemons into lemonade.

00:40:15.150 --> 00:40:17.820
And I did a post-mortem
or in this case

00:40:17.820 --> 00:40:20.120
an autopsy of what I
did wrong and identified

00:40:20.120 --> 00:40:26.670
three errors, two of which
we're going to get to shortly.

00:40:26.670 --> 00:40:29.050
And I realized that I never
wanted to be in a position

00:40:29.050 --> 00:40:32.410
where I was down
25% on a portfolio.

00:40:32.410 --> 00:40:37.490
So this leads to position size.

00:40:37.490 --> 00:40:43.930
There is a study by Dr.
Van Tharp of people--

00:40:43.930 --> 00:40:48.130
that they all get a
hypothetical $100,000.

00:40:48.130 --> 00:40:50.115
They all get the same trades.

00:40:50.115 --> 00:40:52.950
The same number
of winning stocks,

00:40:52.950 --> 00:40:54.470
the same number
of losing stocks,

00:40:54.470 --> 00:40:58.720
both in terms of
frequency and magnitude.

00:40:58.720 --> 00:41:02.950
And yet, 50 simulated
trades later,

00:41:02.950 --> 00:41:09.220
the ending balance of capital
ranges from completely

00:41:09.220 --> 00:41:11.878
wipe out to $13 million.

00:41:11.878 --> 00:41:15.500
And Dr. Thorpe says the reason
for this is position sizing

00:41:15.500 --> 00:41:19.355
and in psychology.

00:41:19.355 --> 00:41:21.480
So if you want to learn
more about position sizing,

00:41:21.480 --> 00:41:24.900
I recommend this book.

00:41:24.900 --> 00:41:27.750
This brings us to
step five, sell.

00:41:27.750 --> 00:41:30.030
What's your exit strategy?

00:41:30.030 --> 00:41:34.590
Before China Media Express, my
exit strategy was qualitative.

00:41:34.590 --> 00:41:36.930
Position size gets
too big, maybe I

00:41:36.930 --> 00:41:41.090
thought that the intrinsic value
of the company was declining,

00:41:41.090 --> 00:41:43.317
maybe I thought I had a
better idea elsewhere.

00:41:46.300 --> 00:41:48.410
Since China Media Express,
I realize that I've

00:41:48.410 --> 00:41:53.200
got behavioral limits.

00:41:53.200 --> 00:41:58.965
And so I wanted to introduce
some objective criteria

00:41:58.965 --> 00:42:03.610
so I never turned small
loss into a big loss.

00:42:03.610 --> 00:42:06.420
And so I'm going to go
through these items right now.

00:42:06.420 --> 00:42:08.070
The first thing
I want to mention

00:42:08.070 --> 00:42:09.550
is that selling is hard.

00:42:09.550 --> 00:42:13.330
You've probably heard
this famous quotation

00:42:13.330 --> 00:42:14.940
by Vince Lombardi.

00:42:14.940 --> 00:42:18.080
Just put it into human
terms-- when you're a kid

00:42:18.080 --> 00:42:21.370
and your mother was reading to
you when you were in your bed,

00:42:21.370 --> 00:42:25.040
did your mom ever read to you
stories about great losers?

00:42:25.040 --> 00:42:27.100
Or when you go into
the park, do you ever

00:42:27.100 --> 00:42:29.060
see a statue of a great loser?

00:42:29.060 --> 00:42:29.990
No.

00:42:29.990 --> 00:42:32.290
We weren't wired
to be great losers.

00:42:32.290 --> 00:42:37.260
And yet, as investors,
that costs us money.

00:42:37.260 --> 00:42:40.250
So what I devised are
these safety switches.

00:42:40.250 --> 00:42:42.120
And a safety switch
is simply-- it's

00:42:42.120 --> 00:42:45.770
a button that if you see
the machinery breaking down,

00:42:45.770 --> 00:42:49.140
you just hit that button
and the machinery turns off.

00:42:49.140 --> 00:42:51.940
And this way you
stop the problem

00:42:51.940 --> 00:42:54.500
before it gets even worse.

00:42:54.500 --> 00:42:56.790
So I'm going to go over
four safety switches.

00:42:56.790 --> 00:43:00.770
The first is a simple one.

00:43:00.770 --> 00:43:04.240
Before you buy a
company, you determine,

00:43:04.240 --> 00:43:06.120
what's the maximum
percentage decline

00:43:06.120 --> 00:43:08.570
that you're willing to
let the stock go down?

00:43:08.570 --> 00:43:10.320
Maybe it's 20%.

00:43:10.320 --> 00:43:13.750
So if the stock then goes
down 21%, then you sell.

00:43:13.750 --> 00:43:16.510
No ands ifs or buts.

00:43:16.510 --> 00:43:18.570
I can't tell you what
the correct percentage

00:43:18.570 --> 00:43:20.560
decline is, because
that's like me telling you

00:43:20.560 --> 00:43:22.000
who you should date.

00:43:22.000 --> 00:43:26.145
But, William O'Neil of
Investors Business Daily

00:43:26.145 --> 00:43:30.050
who's an outstanding
investor-- he's

00:43:30.050 --> 00:43:32.300
also written several books.

00:43:32.300 --> 00:43:36.560
His rule of thumb is if a
position declines 7% to 8%

00:43:36.560 --> 00:43:39.460
from its purchase
price, he sells.

00:43:39.460 --> 00:43:43.150
If that's too rigorous, too
quick on the trigger for you,

00:43:43.150 --> 00:43:46.750
maybe you something where
you sell 50% of your position

00:43:46.750 --> 00:43:50.510
if it goes down 10%,
and the other 50% if it

00:43:50.510 --> 00:43:53.080
the decline is 25%.

00:43:53.080 --> 00:43:56.500
But you've got to have
this in writing before you

00:43:56.500 --> 00:44:00.310
buy the stock because
once you own that stock,

00:44:00.310 --> 00:44:02.840
you get all these
emotional bias kicking in.

00:44:02.840 --> 00:44:06.880
There's a study
about coffee mugs.

00:44:06.880 --> 00:44:11.910
A Nobel Prize was won by
Daniel Kahneman over the notion

00:44:11.910 --> 00:44:15.980
that we'll pay $3
for a coffee mug

00:44:15.980 --> 00:44:20.440
but we won't sell it unless
you offer us about $7.

00:44:20.440 --> 00:44:22.710
That just doesn't make
any sense rationally.

00:44:22.710 --> 00:44:25.040
But it gives you an idea
of some of these challenges

00:44:25.040 --> 00:44:26.880
that we have at selling.

00:44:26.880 --> 00:44:28.840
I want to point out
that sometimes you

00:44:28.840 --> 00:44:31.550
may not be able to get a bid
if you're trying to sell.

00:44:31.550 --> 00:44:34.390
You may say, all right, I'm
going to sell at 7% to 8%

00:44:34.390 --> 00:44:38.320
or I'm going to sell
50% if I'm down 10%.

00:44:38.320 --> 00:44:44.510
In this LinkedIn, in one
day last week it fell 35%.

00:44:44.510 --> 00:44:47.310
You're not going to be
able to get in until you

00:44:47.310 --> 00:44:50.520
get that 35% lower number.

00:44:50.520 --> 00:44:53.590
So this is why position
sizing is important.

00:44:53.590 --> 00:44:56.220
You've go to get that
position size correct,

00:44:56.220 --> 00:44:58.529
even before you own the stock.

00:44:58.529 --> 00:45:00.570
Now, Warren Buffett has
said his favorite holding

00:45:00.570 --> 00:45:01.620
period is forever.

00:45:01.620 --> 00:45:07.140
And that is true if you buy
and hold the right company.

00:45:07.140 --> 00:45:09.444
If you buy and hold
a Microsoft or some

00:45:09.444 --> 00:45:10.485
of these other companies.

00:45:10.485 --> 00:45:13.170
But if you buy and
hold the wrong company,

00:45:13.170 --> 00:45:15.044
then you could get wiped out.

00:45:15.044 --> 00:45:17.210
I want to show you a chart
of a couple of companies.

00:45:17.210 --> 00:45:20.000
Uranium Resources--
this company would've

00:45:20.000 --> 00:45:24.315
turned a hypothetical
$10,000 into $17.

00:45:24.315 --> 00:45:28.400
That's a 99.84% decline.

00:45:28.400 --> 00:45:32.136
And Arch Coal, this would have
turned a hypothetical $10,000

00:45:32.136 --> 00:45:35.810
into $2.81.

00:45:35.810 --> 00:45:38.280
If you don't have
a safety switch,

00:45:38.280 --> 00:45:41.330
you could ride one of
these things to zero.

00:45:41.330 --> 00:45:44.400
And you get into this
point where I'm 25%,

00:45:44.400 --> 00:45:45.631
you may even double down.

00:45:45.631 --> 00:45:54.000
That is-- you can blow up
your portfolio quickly.

00:45:54.000 --> 00:45:56.970
The second safety switch
is what I call the 1% rule.

00:45:56.970 --> 00:46:01.510
So let's say you have a
hypothetical $100,000 portfolio

00:46:01.510 --> 00:46:06.660
and you say, I willing to
lose a maximum of $1,000

00:46:06.660 --> 00:46:08.350
on any position.

00:46:08.350 --> 00:46:10.570
And so you can come up
with different scenarios

00:46:10.570 --> 00:46:12.720
depending upon
how much you think

00:46:12.720 --> 00:46:14.930
you might lose on
a percentage basis

00:46:14.930 --> 00:46:18.280
before that stock then goes
up to its intrinsic value.

00:46:18.280 --> 00:46:20.830
And the idea here is--
these are four scenarios.

00:46:20.830 --> 00:46:25.510
A utility has historically
been a low volatility stock.

00:46:25.510 --> 00:46:28.070
And then the highest
volatility stocks

00:46:28.070 --> 00:46:29.750
would be companies
that are pre-revenue.

00:46:29.750 --> 00:46:33.680
So you can use this approach to
think about what your position

00:46:33.680 --> 00:46:35.145
sizing should be.

00:46:35.145 --> 00:46:36.770
And the great thing
about this approach

00:46:36.770 --> 00:46:41.820
is if you use the 1% rule, you
can have 10 successive losers

00:46:41.820 --> 00:46:44.710
and you still have
90% of your capital.

00:46:44.710 --> 00:46:47.130
So that's a discipline
repeatable and explainable

00:46:47.130 --> 00:46:49.410
process that will protect you.

00:46:49.410 --> 00:46:53.090
The third safety switch is
what I call reward to risk.

00:46:53.090 --> 00:46:56.900
So let's say that
the stock's $50

00:46:56.900 --> 00:46:58.680
and you think it's worth $65.

00:46:58.680 --> 00:47:01.950
So your upside-- you're
expected profit is $15.

00:47:01.950 --> 00:47:05.090
Now the smart money
says, have a reward

00:47:05.090 --> 00:47:07.120
to risk ratio of at least three.

00:47:07.120 --> 00:47:09.650
That's investing
probabilistically.

00:47:09.650 --> 00:47:12.960
That means you're going
to bet $1 to make $3.

00:47:12.960 --> 00:47:14.525
You don't want to
bet a $1 to make $2

00:47:14.525 --> 00:47:16.830
or bet a $1 to make a $1.

00:47:16.830 --> 00:47:18.920
That doesn't make sense.

00:47:18.920 --> 00:47:26.860
So if then you buy the
stock and it goes up to $65,

00:47:26.860 --> 00:47:28.880
you've made three
times your bet.

00:47:28.880 --> 00:47:30.710
So congratulations.

00:47:30.710 --> 00:47:33.770
Let's say you hang on and
it keeps going up to $75.

00:47:33.770 --> 00:47:35.290
Now you've made
five times your bet.

00:47:35.290 --> 00:47:37.760
That's even better.

00:47:37.760 --> 00:47:41.340
However, let's say the
stock goes down to $45.

00:47:41.340 --> 00:47:43.900
Well, you've bet
$5, you've lost $5.

00:47:43.900 --> 00:47:46.150
So now you're minus one.

00:47:46.150 --> 00:47:51.352
My recommendation is
this is where you sell.

00:47:51.352 --> 00:47:53.850
If you're going to have a
stock that's losing money,

00:47:53.850 --> 00:47:55.710
you never want to lose
more than your bet.

00:47:55.710 --> 00:47:59.000
So this is the demarcation.

00:47:59.000 --> 00:48:02.970
If however, you're too
stubborn and you're not

00:48:02.970 --> 00:48:07.590
able to sell when the stock goes
down $10, now you're down two.

00:48:07.590 --> 00:48:11.830
And then if you're hanging
on and it goes down to $25,

00:48:11.830 --> 00:48:14.690
now you're at minus five.

00:48:14.690 --> 00:48:16.090
So all I can say,
if you're going

00:48:16.090 --> 00:48:19.210
to invest in a-- if
you have a stock that's

00:48:19.210 --> 00:48:23.710
going down sell it a minus one.

00:48:23.710 --> 00:48:26.160
Our fourth safety switch,
price-moving average-- now

00:48:26.160 --> 00:48:31.180
