01:10:20.270 --> 01:10:25.230
four times since it went public.

01:10:25.230 --> 01:10:28.270
So even the bluest
of blue chips can

01:10:28.270 --> 01:10:30.690
suffer those kinds of decline.

01:10:30.690 --> 01:10:33.440
And the other thing
I want to point out

01:10:33.440 --> 01:10:37.360
is, let's see you
misunderestimate

01:10:37.360 --> 01:10:41.680
how far a company falls.

01:10:41.680 --> 01:10:46.580
And you follow your strategy
and you sell your position.

01:10:46.580 --> 01:10:49.240
You don't have to-- that
doesn't mean that you

01:10:49.240 --> 01:10:51.150
can't buy that position back.

01:10:51.150 --> 01:10:54.966
What you could do is you say,
OK, I'll buy it back in--

01:10:54.966 --> 01:10:58.810
say I'll buy back
25% of my position

01:10:58.810 --> 01:11:01.774
after the next 10Q or
the next 10K is filed.

01:11:01.774 --> 01:11:03.315
And if there's a
smoking gun, if it's

01:11:03.315 --> 01:11:07.140
a company-specific
reason-- fraud,

01:11:07.140 --> 01:11:10.140
something else, some reason
that you don't know about,

01:11:10.140 --> 01:11:12.030
but maybe leads
to your investors

01:11:12.030 --> 01:11:14.570
do and that's why the
price is declining,

01:11:14.570 --> 01:11:17.020
well you wait until the
next SEC filing comes out

01:11:17.020 --> 01:11:19.830
and then you buy back your
position, starting say 25%

01:11:19.830 --> 01:11:21.940
a quarter for four
quarters, then

01:11:21.940 --> 01:11:24.240
you're back to your
original position.

01:11:24.240 --> 01:11:27.490
So you can have these
work-arounds and these apps

01:11:27.490 --> 01:11:30.110
to help you get back
into a position.

01:11:30.110 --> 01:11:33.260
If you think you're
selling Microsoft in 1991

01:11:33.260 --> 01:11:36.790
or Berkshire Hathaway in 1975.

01:11:36.790 --> 01:11:39.220
MALE SPEAKER: We have time
